Another important characteristic of the new carbon materials is the possibility to design and build hybrid or hierarchical materials [14]. We define these nano-architectural materials as the third generation of nanocarbons (Figure 3
                     ). An interesting example, with great interest to develop improved systems for producing solar fuels, is given from TiO2-nanocarbons (CNTs, graphene, etc.) hybrids [15,16]. Figure 4
                      shows an example of TiO2 nanoparticles over graphene acting as electron acceptor to enhance charge separation and improve the performance of TiO2 in water photoelectrolysis. Nanocarbons can also act as electron donors, i.e. photosensitisers (carbon quantum dots), as will be discussed later. In addition, the intrinsic properties of TiO2 are changed by this interaction with nanocarbons, creating hybrid materials [15,16]. The advantages of nanomaterials in photochemical applications are manifold [16–20]. The nanocarbons can 1) transfer electrons into an inorganic compound and act as a photosensitiser in extending the absorption range; 2) accept photoexcited electrons from the inorganic compound, thus separating them from the photoactive holes; 3) conduct away excess heat during the catalytic reaction; 4) act as a template and heat sink to stabilise smaller catalyst particles whose larger specific surface area can convert more reactant molecules; and 5) reduce the amount of active catalyst, decrease their weight and improve cycling ability and overall life time. In most cases, the obtained hybrid or composite materials with hierarchical structures have a strong synergistic effect in combining the advantage of the two building blocks.

Another interesting possibility is the development of advanced Z-schemes for water splitting [22]. One of the main approaches for achieving water splitting using visible light is to apply a two-step photoexcitation mechanism between two different photocatalysts (Figure 6a
                     ). This process was inspired by natural photosynthesis in green plants and is known as the Z-scheme. In the two-step systems, the water splitting reaction is broken up into two stages: one for H2 evolution and the other for O2 evolution; these are combined by using a shuttle redox couple (Red/Ox, for example the I3
                     −/I− pair) in the solution. Over a H2 evolution photocatalyst, the photoexcited electrons reduce water to H2 and holes in the valence band oxidize the reductant (Red) to an oxidant (Ox). The oxidant is reduced back to the reductant by photoexcited electrons generated over an O2 evolution photocatalyst, where the holes oxidize water to O2. This system lowers the energy required for photocatalysis, allowing visible light to be utilized more efficiently than in conventional water-splitting systems. The use of solutions has a number of practical problems when realizing solar cells (sealing, light scattering, etc.). A recent interesting development is based on the use of photoreduced graphene oxide as a solid electron mediator for water splitting in the Z-scheme photocatalysis system (Figure 6b) [23]. The graphene sheet can shuttle photogenerated electrons from an O2-evolving photocatalyst (BiVO4) to a H2-evolving photocatalyst (Ru/SrTiO3:Rh), triplicating the consumption of electron-hole pairs in the water splitting reaction under visible-light irradiation. Even though the overall performance is still unsatisfactory (about 8–10 mmol H2/h in H2SO4 aqueous solution using a 300 W Xe lamp as light source with a 420 nm cut-off filter), the example shows the potential to use advanced hybrid nanoarchitectures based on nanocarbons for producing solar fuels.

Various aspects have to be considered in nanocarbon-semiconductor hybrid materials [16]:


                                 •

nanocarbons offer an effective way for an efficient dispersion of the semiconductor preventing from agglomeration, also providing an hierarchical structure for an efficient light harvesting, and eventually for easy access from gas/liquid phase components (in photocatalytic reactions) or electrolyte (in DSSC);


                                 •

interfacial interaction between the nanocarbons and semiconductor particles stabilizes different morphologies of the supported semiconductor nanoparticles, which in turn influences the performances;


                                 •

interaction of semiconductors with nanocarbons induces modification of the intrinsic properties of the semiconductor particles (band gap, charge carrier density, lifetime of charge separation, non-radiative paths, etc.) as well as the surface properties;


                                 •

carbon nanodots and other carbon surface species may act as efficient solid-state sensitizers to promote visible light absorption. Carbons may also be doped to the semiconductors (TiO2), inducing a shift in the band edge towards the visible region;


                                 •

nanocarbons may show excellent electronic conductivity, but defects and other aspects can decrease largely the conductivity;


                                 •

nanocarbon hybrids with semiconductors can act as sinks for electrons, enhancing the lifetime of charge separation. Fermi levels of the nanocarbons are generally below the conduction band, and are minimum of most semiconductors. However, depending on the specific characteristics of the nanocarbons, the Fermi level may also result above that of TiO2;


                                 •

due to their thermal conductivity, nanocarbons can help in maintaining more uniformly the temperature of the semiconductor-nanocarbon hybrid upon irradiation;


                                 •

a further role of the nanocarbons is to provide an optimal nano-architecture in the photoanode for light absorption.
